nvestigate the origin of words (lexical etymology) but also structural elements, such as morphemes and constructions (structural etymology). This pioneer volume assembles thirteen etymological studies over a broad range of languages, ranging from Europe to Australia and the Pacific, focusing in particular on Australian Indigenous languages. The phenomena investigated in the contributions comprise the origin of Australian Indigenous place names and kinship terms, constructions and word histories in Oceanic languages, typological investigations as well as papers on the methodology of etymological research. This volume is intended for a scholarly audience including intermediate and advanced university students with an interest in historical linguistic, especially in etymology, but also semantics, toponymy and language contact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAustralian languagesxEtymology. 0aOceanic languagesxEtymology. 4aEtymologie. 4aLinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAustralian Indigenous Languages.  aHistorical Lingusitics.  aLexical Etymology.  aStructural Etymology.1 aFrançois, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiacon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendery, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHercus, Luise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMailhammer, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMailhammer, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcConvall, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNash, David, econtri